Here is the translation:

This divine self dwells within, performs devotion to God's greatness; 
The devotee Bhagavadasa, worships Lord Dasa without end.

Here is the translation:

This lowly woman is beautiful, worships Hari who stays with bravery; 
The twice-born devotee is Vajlibhai, a Koli Harijan of Mithibai.

The two-couplet is:

Dvi-j Kanku Adi-t Acharat, Maan-kunvarya Che Hari-bhakta;
Kadiya Bhakta Che Kawal-Ram, Ehaadi Jan Nadia-d Gama.

Translated to English, it reads:

Two-twice Kanku, the one who is doing, is a devotee of God; 
The devotee is only Ram, and this village, Nadia-d Gama.

This is the original couplet:

"Ahadi jan agninit, sarve janne svamishun prit;
Dharm niyam dhari nar-nary, na lkhay che aparampara."

Translated to English, it becomes:

"This is the first origin, unknown to all people; I will be the lord of all beings, in love with everyone;
Following the law and norms of religion, we shall not be forgotten forever."
